         <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.6856" xml:lang="en">
            <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
            <dateline>23.1.90</dateline>
            <opener>Dear Sir and friend,</opener>
            <p>You may be right indeed, but now, pray consider this: if I were to contest that <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">trembler</hi> proceeds from <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">tremulare</hi>, you would instantly quote a number of similar processes sufficient to convince me; if I deny that <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">aller</hi> can proceed from <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
ambulare</hi>, you may only appeal to my good faith and common sense.<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Möglicherweise Bezug auf <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.92">Schuchardt, „Andare, etc.“, Romania 17, 1888, 417-421</ref>.</note> That is, I mean, the superiority of the phonetic standard to the semantic: the former affords scientific certainty, the latter mere probability. Now, if you do not understand it as I, I must infer that we have not „le crâne fait de même“ (Musset),<note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">
                  <persName ref="[authorityLink]">Alfred de Musset</persName>, <bibl>
                     <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Premières poésies</hi>, XXXVI/XXXVII.
</bibl>
               </note> and I am sorry for it, for yours is a remarkably well made.</p>
            <closer>
               <salute>Yours truly</salute>
               <signed>
                  <persName ref="[authorityLink]">V. Henry</persName>
               </signed>
            </closer>
            <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
         </div>
